String Types:
            1. String literal
            2. new String
String pool: saves String literals
if you create more than 1 string literal object, it will be created only one object in the pool.

        String s1 = "Cat";

        String s2 = "Dog";

        String s3 = "Cat";

        String s4 = "Cat";

        System.out.println(s1==s3);  // true
        System.out.println(s1==s4);  // true
        System.out.println(s3==s4);  // true
        System.out.println(s1==s2);  // false

Creating String object by new keyword:

    . Creates new different object in the heap

    String str1 = new String ("Java");
    String str2 = new String ("Java");

  // str1==str2 returns false, because they are 2 different objects even though they print the same thing



index Number:

        Every character in string has an index number
        Index number starts from ZERO
        index number can not be negatif, never less than 0


    String Methods

    charAt();   :   used in order to print index number

    length();   :   used in order to find out, how many character is in String,
                    "Wooden Spoon"
                     01234567891011
                    char f = s1.charAt(0);
                    int lastIndexNum = s1.length() - 1;
                    char l =s1.charAt(1);
                    System.out.println(f + " : " + l);
    equals();  equals is case sensitive



